---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
import Cta from "../components/sections/Cta.astro";
import Button from "../components/Button.astro";
import { PAPER, LINKS } from "../site";

const ARROW = `<path d="M5 12h14"/><path d="m12 5 7 7-7 7"/>`;
---

<Layout
  title="The science"
  description="Every protein draws on a supply of charged tRNAs. Andon measures that supply directly — single-molecule, published in Nature Communications, and validated from bacteria to mammalian cells."
>
  {/* Hero */}
  <section class="px-6 pt-20 pb-16 md:px-10 md:pt-28 md:pb-20">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-[46rem]">
      <h1
        class="rise text-balance font-display text-4xl font-extrabold leading-[1.05] tracking-[-0.03em] text-ink md:text-[3.5rem]"
      >
        The supply chain behind every protein.
      </h1>
      <p
        class="rise mt-6 max-w-[40rem] text-lg leading-[1.7] text-muted md:text-xl"
        style="animation-delay: 120ms"
      >
        Every protein a cell makes draws on a supply of charged tRNAs: the
        molecules that deliver amino acids to the ribosome. Andon measures that
        supply directly. Here's what it is, how we read it, and what we've found.
      </p>
      <div class="rise mt-10 h-px w-24 bg-accent" style="animation-delay: 220ms">
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* Beat 1 — THE MECHANISM */}
  <section class="px-6 py-12 md:px-10 md:py-16">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-[46rem]">
      <span
        class="font-button text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-accent-700"
      >
        The mechanism
      </span>
      <h2
        class="mt-3 text-balance font-display text-3xl font-bold leading-[1.1] tracking-[-0.02em] text-ink md:text-[2.5rem]"
      >
        Protein production runs on a supply most people never see.
      </h2>
      <div class="mt-6 space-y-5 text-lg leading-[1.75] text-muted">
        <p>
          Proteins are built from amino acids, assembled in a precise order by
          the ribosome. The molecules that deliver those amino acids are tRNAs:
          each one carries a specific amino acid to the ribosome at the moment
          it's needed. A tRNA loaded with its amino acid is charged; an empty one
          is not. Production only moves as fast as the right charged tRNAs arrive.
          When a cell is pushed to overproduce a protein, demand for certain
          charged tRNAs can outrun supply, and the ribosome stalls, waiting.
        </p>
        <p>
          That supply isn't fixed. It rises and falls during production, in ways
          no one could see.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* Beat 2 — THE METHOD. Body left, schematic right. */}
  <section class="px-6 py-12 md:px-10 md:py-16">
    <div
      class="mx-auto grid max-w-[78rem] items-center gap-10 lg:grid-cols-[1fr_0.85fr] lg:gap-16"
    >
      <div>
        <span
          class="font-button text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-accent-700"
        >
          The chemistry
        </span>
        <h2
          class="mt-3 text-balance font-display text-3xl font-bold leading-[1.1] tracking-[-0.02em] text-ink md:text-[2.5rem]"
        >
          We keep the signal everything else throws away.
        </h2>
        <div class="mt-6 space-y-5 text-lg leading-[1.7] text-muted">
          <p>
            The amino acid on a charged tRNA is the signal that it's ready to
            build protein, and it's easily lost: it falls off on its own, and
            standard sequencing prep strips off whatever remains. Either way, the
            charge information is gone before anything gets read.
          </p>
          <p>
            Our chemistry preserves it instead, holding the amino acid in place so
            each tRNA can be sequenced with its charge intact. Every molecule is
            then read individually by nanopore, and for every tRNA, we see whether
            it was charged or empty.
          </p>
          <p>
            The same read resolves three things at once: the tRNA's sequence, its
            modifications, and which amino acid it carried.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
      {/* SCHEMATIC SLOT — graphic to be provided by Laura. Drop the <img> / SVG
          (3-step: amino acid lost → locked on → nanopore read) in here. */}
      <figure class="rise" style="animation-delay: 120ms">
        <div
          class="flex aspect-[4/3] w-full items-center justify-center rounded-2xl border border-dashed border-line bg-surface/50 p-8 text-center"
        >
          <span
            class="font-button text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.16em] text-faint"
          >
            Schematic — to be provided
          </span>
        </div>
      </figure>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* Beat 3 — THE FINDING. Copy only, no figure. */}
  <section class="px-6 py-12 md:px-10 md:py-16">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-[46rem]">
      <span
        class="font-button text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-accent-700"
      >
        The finding
      </span>
      <h2
        class="mt-3 text-balance font-display text-3xl font-bold leading-[1.1] tracking-[-0.02em] text-ink md:text-[2.5rem]"
      >
        What we've found: charging shifts during production.
      </h2>
      <div class="mt-6 space-y-5 text-lg leading-[1.75] text-muted">
        <p>
          We measured tRNA charging in cells overproducing protein, and found
          that it shifts as production runs, in patterns specific to the protein
          being made. The supply isn't a fixed background the cell draws on
          evenly. It responds to what's being built, running short for some tRNAs
          while others hold steady.
        </p>
        <p>
          This is a layer of protein production that has never been measured
          before, and it's the foundation we're building prediction on.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* Beat 4 — the published / patent-pending method. Publication card. */}
  <section class="border-t border-line/60 px-6 py-20 md:px-10 md:py-28">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-[72rem]">
      <span
        class="font-button text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-accent-700"
      >
        The method
      </span>
      <h2
        class="mt-3 text-balance font-display text-3xl font-bold leading-[1.1] tracking-[-0.02em] text-ink md:text-[2.5rem]"
      >
        Published and patent-pending.
      </h2>
      <p class="mt-5 max-w-[42rem] text-lg leading-[1.7] text-muted">
        <em>Nature Communications</em>, 2025. Now validated from microbial to
        mammalian systems. WO/2025/250601.
      </p>

      <article
        class="mt-10 overflow-hidden rounded-2xl border border-line/70 bg-surface"
      >
        <div class="flex flex-col gap-7 p-7 sm:flex-row sm:gap-8 md:p-9">
          <a
            href={PAPER.url}
            target="_blank"
            rel="noopener"
            class="group shrink-0 self-start"
            aria-label="Read the paper — opens the article in Nature Communications"
          >
            <img
              src="/figures/paper-natcomms.jpg"
              alt="First page of the paper in Nature Communications"
              width="720"
              height="957"
              loading="lazy"
              class="w-36 rounded-lg border border-line/70 shadow-sm transition-transform duration-200 group-hover:-translate-y-0.5 sm:w-44"
            />
          </a>
          <div>
            <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center gap-3">
              <span
                class="rounded-full bg-accent/15 px-3 py-1 font-button text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.14em] text-accent-700"
              >
                Open access
              </span>
              <span
                class="font-button text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.14em] text-faint"
              >
                {PAPER.journal} · {PAPER.year}
              </span>
            </div>
            <h3
              class="mt-5 font-display text-xl font-bold leading-snug tracking-tight text-ink md:text-2xl"
            >
              {PAPER.title}
            </h3>
            <p class="mt-4 text-[0.95rem] leading-[1.7] text-muted">
              {PAPER.authors}
              <span class="text-faint"> {PAPER.citation}</span>
            </p>
            <div class="mt-6">
              <Button
                href={PAPER.url}
                variant="secondary"
                size="default"
                target="_blank"
                rel="noopener"
              >
                Read the paper
              </Button>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* Beat 5 — vision + talk. Dark band. */}
  <section class="bg-navy px-6 py-20 text-paper md:px-10 md:py-28">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-[60rem]">
      <h2
        class="text-balance font-display text-3xl font-bold leading-[1.1] tracking-[-0.02em] md:text-[2.5rem]"
      >
        From measurements to models.
      </h2>
      <p class="mt-5 max-w-[42rem] text-lg leading-[1.7] text-paper-muted">
        Charging shifts in protein-specific ways, which means it's learnable.
        Measure it across enough proteins and systems, and the rules connecting a
        sequence to how well a cell can build it come into view. That's the path
        from measurement to prediction.
      </p>

      <a
        href={LINKS.londonCallingWatch}
        target="_blank"
        rel="noopener"
        class="mt-8 inline-flex items-center gap-2 font-button text-sm tracking-wide text-accent transition-colors hover:text-accent-400"
      >
        The method, presented at London Calling
        <svg
          width="16"
          height="16"
          viewBox="0 0 24 24"
          fill="none"
          stroke="currentColor"
          stroke-width="2"
          stroke-linecap="round"
          stroke-linejoin="round"
          aria-hidden="true"
          set:html={ARROW}
        />
      </a>
      <div
        class="mt-5 aspect-video w-full overflow-hidden rounded-2xl border border-line-dark bg-navy-soft"
      >
        <iframe
          class="h-full w-full"
          src={LINKS.londonCallingEmbed}
          title="The method, presented at London Calling"
          loading="lazy"
          allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share"
          referrerpolicy="strict-origin-when-cross-origin"
          allowfullscreen></iframe>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <Cta
    heading="Bring this measurement to your system."
    body="If you express a lot of protein, the supply behind it has never been visible. Let's take a look."
    cta="Let's take a look"
  />
</Layout>
